        <section id="getting-started" class="card">
            <h2>Getting started</h2>
            <p>
                You don’t need much space to begin. Many gardeners start with <em>containers</em> on a windowsill.
                Begin by observing how sunlight moves across your space during the day. Most vegetables need
                <strong>at least 6 hours</strong> of direct sun.
            </p>

            <h3>Quick checklist</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Sunlight: 6–8 hours for fruiting plants, 3–5 for leafy greens.</li>
                <li>Water access: A hose or watering can within easy reach.</li>
                <li>Soil: Loose, rich in organic matter, drains well.</li>
                <li>Containers: Drainage holes are non-negotiable.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Beginner project (ordered steps)</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Choose 3 easy plants: basil, lettuce, cherry tomatoes.</li>
                <li>Fill a container with potting mix; avoid heavy garden soil.</li>
                <li>Plant seedlings at recommended spacing; label each variety.</li>
                <li>Water thoroughly; keep soil moist while roots establish.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Key terms (definition list)</h3>
            <dl>
                <dt>Mulch</dt>
                <dd>Material layered on top of soil to reduce evaporation and suppress weeds.</dd>
                <dt>Hardening off</dt>
                <dd>Gradually introducing seedlings to outdoor conditions before planting.</dd>
                <dt>Deadheading</dt>
                <dd>Removing spent flowers to encourage new blooms.</dd>
            </dl>

            <blockquote cite="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gardening">
                “Gardening adds years to your life and life to your years.” <cite>— Anonymous</cite>
            </blockquote>
